		<header>
			
			<h1>Measures taken in Senegal to counter onion imports and support local production </h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 July 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In February 2013, the government of Senegal brought forward to February the introduction of seasonal restriction on imports of onions from its planned introduction date in April. However, these measures did not prove entirely effective, and in April 2013 the government announced a tightening up of port inspection, in order to prevent imports of containerised shipments of onions, and the planned introduction of a new system of import licence allocations to facilitate the granting of these “to importers who commit to promote the marketing of local production”. No more details have been provided but, more recently, the government has announced that for next season the import ban will take effect from October 2013.</p><p>The measures followed complaints from onion producers that traders were undermining the effectiveness of seasonal restrictions by stockpiling onions before the start of the ban and releasing them onto the market during the closed import season.</p><p>Meanwhile, a study published in <i>Cahier Agricultures</i> in March/April,<i>&nbsp;</i>comparing production and marketing systems in Niger and Benin, has highlighted the advantages of the Niger onion industry compared to that in Benin. The Niger onion industry not only satisfies its entire domestic market but also exports extensively to regional markets. In contrast, Benin continues to import a significant volume of national consumption.</p><p>Beyond soil conditions, production cost and yield advantages, the study notes that the Niger industry has benefited from:</p>
<ul>

<li>better-organised producer associations linked to particular wholesalers who deal with marketing; </li>

<li>good storage and conservation techniques; and </li>

<li>a generally better-organised supply chain. </li>

</ul>
<p>Considerations related to flavour ensure that onions from Niger enjoy a good reputation, which enables higher prices to be obtained. The inclusion of the onion industry in the national country strategy is also seen as an important factor in fostering a better structuring of the onion supply chain in Niger.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>APS, ‘Sénégal : Gel des importations d'oignons du 10 février au 31 août’, 5 February 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/201302051044.html " target="_self">http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/201302051044.html</a></p><p>Senegal Ministry of Trade, ‘Oignon, le Ministre Alioune Sarr decide le blocage de l’oignon importé au port’, 10 April 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.commerce.gouv.sn/article.php3?id_article=233#sthash.2JnX56zu.vCsF2cZn.dpuf" target="_self">http://www.commerce.gouv.sn/article.php3?id_article=233#sthash.2JnX56zu....</a></p><p><i>Cahiers Agricultures</i>, ‘Filières oignon en Afrique de l’Ouest : étude comparée des filières nigérienne et béninoise’, Volume 22, No. 2, pp. 112–123, March–April 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.jle.com/e-docs/00/04/85/50/article.phtml" target="_self">http://www.jle.com/e-docs/00/04/85/50/article.phtml</a></p><p>Senegal Ministry of Trade, ‘Le processus de gel des importations commence à partir&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; d’octobre’, 10 May 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.commerce.gouv.sn/article.php3?id_article=243#sthash.cnhi7roL.dpuf" target="_self">http://www.commerce.gouv.sn/article.php3?id_article=243#sthash.cnhi7roL....</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The emerging strategy in Senegal of establishing a dialogue with traders over local procurement, linked to the allocation of import licences – if transparently and accountably managed in association with a representative stakeholder body – could potentially provide more scope for developing a managed onion market that fosters local production, while meeting consumer requirements.</p><p>This, however, will require the establishment alongside of real-time market information systems that allow producers, traders and retailers to understand each other’s requirements. The proper functioning of this information system would be assisted by the development of an enforceable system of forward contracting for the supply of onions, which can then be used to secure finance for investment in an expansion of both production and quality improvements.</p><p>The review of the experience in Niger would also appear to highlight the importance of strengthening producer organisations, promoting improvements in the structuring of relations along the supply chain, and the need for investments in storage and conservation facilities in production zones under producer control.</p>
		</div>
		
